frameDefinitions: A Cognizer construes an Item as belonging to a certain Category.
This frame describes intentionally formed human social groups (here termed Organizations) with some definite structure and Members.
These words refer to Parts merging to form a Whole.
A Timetable of Events is a mental object deliberately created, modified or kept by a Cognizer.
frameExamples: He <t>arranged</t> the elements in the pattern that we now call the periodic table.
You 've already <t>stereotyped</t> me as a bimbo, have n't you?
The two droplets <t>merge</t>, and then travel down the windowpane even faster.
Changes to an employee's work <t><fex name='tt'>schedule</fex></t> should generally be approved prior to the change actually occuring.
listRoleDefinitions: The person who causes the <fen>Theme</fen> to be in a particular <fen>Configuration</fen>.
An entity that consists of  parts which can be put into a configuration relative to each other and/or relative to their environment.
A state that holds of the <fen>Theme</fen> or a relation that holds among the constituent parts of the <fen>Theme</fen> as a result of the arranging action.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the arranging takes place.
This is the person who performs an act of categorization. Typically, this frame element is expressed as an External Argument.
This is the entity which is construed or treated by the <fen>Cognizer</fen> as being an instance of a particular <fen>Category</fen>. Typically, the <fen>Item</fen> is expressed as an Object.

This frame element expresses a general type or class of which the <fen>Item</fen> is considered an instance. Typically, it is expressed in a prepositional phrase headed by <ment>as</ment> or <ment>under</ment>.

This frame element expresses properties of the <fen>Item</fen> which is used as a basis for categorization. <fen>Criteria</fen> are the general dimensions along which <fen>Item</fen>s can potentially differ from one another and hence, fall into different <fen>Category</fen>s. For example, a paint sample can be classified <ment>by color</ment> or <ment>by finish (matte or gloss)</ment>; if they are classified by color, one can be classified <ment>as orange</ment> and another <ment>as red</ment>. The <fen>Criteria</fen> role is typically expressed as a PP headed by <ment>by</ment>, or as a complex PP of the form <ment>on the basis of...</ment>:
This Frame Element marks expressions that indicate when a certain Categorization was made.
The entity of which the individuals are <fen>Members</fen>.
A person belonging to an <fen>Organization</fen>.
This role describes the general location where the <fen>Organization</fen> operates, but does not indicate the possessor of the <fen>Organization</fen>.
The entities that merge to form a single <fen>Whole</fen>.
The single, undifferentiated entity that is the result of the amalgamation.
The prominent entity that combines with <fen>Part_2</fen> to form a <fen>Whole</fen>.
The less focussed-upon entity that the <fen>Part_1</fen> merges with.
The time at which the <fen>Parts</fen> become amalgamated into a <fen>Whole</fen>
The location at which the amalgamation occurs.
The mental schedule of times at which the <fen>Events</fen> are set to take place.
The events which are to take place at specified times acording to the <fen>Timetable</fen>.
The sentient entity who keeps the <fen>Timetable</fen>.
listRoleExamples: <fex>Kim</fex> categorized the books under fiction. <fex>Kim</fex> categorized them on the basis of genre.
The students were categorized <fex>on the basis of their test scores</fex>.
<fex>20 years ago</fex> people would consider this as nothing unusual
They had all just merged <fex>into one big file</fex>.
<fex>The single smaller soul</fex> merges with the Ur-soul.
The single smaller soul merges <fex>with the Ur-soul</fex>.
My idiot friend forgot his class <fex>schedule</fex> again.
What's your <fex>class</fex> schedule like this spring?
